abstract: CHICAGO, June 30. -- Mary Beaufort won the five-thousand-dollar Horse Review Stakes at Washington Park to-day with ease. There was practically nothing in the race to make her travel at her best. Bessie Wilton took the 2:19 trot handily in straight heats after the first. The field was too large to handle well. abstract: CHICAGO, July 4. -- The Pullman bicycle road rate was run this morning over a fast course and was won by Edward Hell, a seven-minute man. Alfred Schmidt, with an allowance of 8 minutes, finished second, and E.A. Wilson, a six-and-a-half-minute man, third. The start of the race was made in front of the Auditorium Hotel, on Michigan Avenue, and the finish at Pullman, a distance of sixteen miles.

abstract: HAVANA, July 4. -- Coi. Drualla reports that, with 620 men, he left the Conchita estate, near Boiondron, Province of Matanzas, and, marching toward Majagua, found the rebel parties commanded by Lacret, Roque, and other leaders, occupying strong positions behind stone fences. abstract: The past week, so far as real estate dealings go, has been typical of the season. The customary dullness has been emphasized a bit by the holiday. Many brokers and operators are out of town and are apt to remain away for several weeks to come. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, July 5. -- Quarrels over trivial causes cost the lives of two men today. Bartholomew Chambley, twenty-eight years old, and Joseph Kennedy, twentyfour years old, disputed last night over the price of a drink, and Kennedy knocked, Chambley down, fracturing his skull. Chambley was arrested later in the night for drunkenness, and when the police got him to the station house, they discovered his injury.

abstract: -- Mortimer L. Fell died on Sunday at his home, 19 West Eighty-fourth Street, from pneumonia. He was engaged in the cloth business for a number of years in this city, and lived in Morristown, N.J., until four years ago, when the family moved to this city.

abstract: BOSTON, July 9. -- Local stocks were exceedingly dull. The only interest shown was in a few of the coppers. Prices generally fell below last night's closing, and the market at the close was inclined to weakness. Montana dropped 1 1/8, to 85 1/2, but recovered to 86. Old Dominion lost 1, to 14 3/4, but closed at 15. Tamarack declined 4 1/2, to 78, where it closed.

abstract: CHICAGO, July 11. -- The promised revival in business to-day did not materialize, but, as this was Saturday, that was probably an excuse for the inactivity. abstract: BOSTON, July 11. -- The market for local stocks to-day was very much restricted. Montana was practically the only active stock. It opened up 1 2/4, to 87 3/4, and advanced to 88 1/2. The rise was caused partly by short covering. Tamarack recovered the 5 points it lost yesterday, to 77, and closed at 76. Old Dominion rose 5/8, to 13 7/8. The balance of the market was dull and firm.

abstract: PROVIDENCE, July 11. -- Local stocks during the week have been extremely quiet. Investors, as a rule, are inclined to wait for lower prices, and, as a result, there has been little or no trading. abstract: FLUSHING, L.I., July 18. -- The eleventh annual regatta of the Long Island Rowing Association was held to-day in Flushing Bay. Numerous small craft, crowded with sightseers, were about the waters early, and waited patiently for the beginning of the day's programme. The first event was scheduled for 2:30 o'clock, but it was two hours later before the men took their positions at the stakeboat, while the final event was rowed in almost darkness.
